## ARCHITECTURE — ATOMIC DESIGN

Components are organized into 4 levels:
- **Atoms** — smallest building blocks (Button, Typography, Icon, Input, Badge, etc.)
- **Molecules** — composed from atoms (MenuItem, Menu, ButtonIcon, Breadcrumb, InputText, etc.)
- **Organisms** — complex sections (Navbar, Footer, PageHeader)
- **Templates** — pure UI main content of page layouts, NO logic, NO Redux, NO routing

To accomodate the best practice of NextJS routing, place files in app folder under the designated folder.
There will be several files under the route grouping folder such as;
- **Page** — HOC layer, ALL logic lives here (Redux hooks, useRouter, event handlers, etc.), the file name should follow the uri
- **Layout** — layout of entire web page that will be rendered

**Rule:** If you're writing useState, useEffect, useRouter, or useAppSelector — you're in a Page. If you're writing JSX — you're in a Template.

To make testing easy:
- "Template" from atomic design = UI Main content
- "Page" from atomic design = connects HOC with the template

